---
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import BookLayout from '../../layouts/BookLayout.astro';
import { buildToc } from '../../lib/toc';
import SnrRange from '../../components/SnrRange.astro';
const toc = buildToc(await getCollection('book'));
---
<BookLayout title="SNR vs distance" toc={toc}>
  <h1>SNR vs distance (field-referred)</h1>
  <p>
    Give a sensor's equivalent input field noise in nT<sub>rms</sub> and a
    generator dipole moment <em>m</em> = N<sub>g</sub>I A<sub>g</sub>, and this tool
    shows how the signal-to-noise ratio falls with range. Working in the
    field domain (nT) instead of volts collapses turns, area, gain and frequency
    into one comparison — <em>how much field the sensor sees</em> versus
    <em>how much field-noise it has</em> — so the same plot serves a coil or a TMR
    sensor (Ch. 8 §8.1, Ch. 15–16).
  </p>
  <p>
    The signal scales as SNR ∝ <em>m</em>/(r³σ<sub>n</sub>): a decade of range costs
    <strong>60 dB</strong>, which is the 1/r³ wall behind every working-volume limit
    (Ch. 9). Two orientation effects sit on top of it. The shaded band is the
    <strong>field-point anisotropy</strong>: |B| runs from ×1 on the equator to ×2 on
    the dipole axis. The decisive one is the <strong>sensor projection</strong>: a
    single-axis coil or field sensor reads |B|·cos φ, so as its axis tilts toward
    broadside (φ → 90°) the signal — and the usable range — collapses to a
    <strong>null at any distance</strong>.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is precisely the orientation dependence the triad CRLB bound (the
    <a href="../crlb/">CRLB explorer</a>, Ch. 24) assumes away: that bound reports how
    well a <em>fully-observed</em> pose can be localized, not whether a given sensor
    axis can see the field at all. Tick <em>show 3-axis</em> to compare against a
    sensor that reads |B| directly — it is φ-invariant, so the null disappears, which
    is the design argument for a triad over a single coil (Ch. 13).
  </p>
  <SnrRange />
  <p class="text-sm text-slate-500">
    Uses the same validated dipole field (<code>dipoleField</code>) as the rest of the
    suite. For the volts-domain view (Johnson noise, induced EMF), see the
    <a href="../noise-budget/">noise-budget calculator</a>; for the resulting pose
    uncertainty, the <a href="../crlb/">CRLB explorer</a> and
    <a href="../working-volume/">working-volume optimizer</a>.
  </p>
</BookLayout>
